                              <history>
                  <origin>
                     Probably <origPlace cert="medium" ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208">India</origPlace> completed on <origDate calendar="#Hijri-qamari" when="1694-12-28">Friday, 14 Ẕī-l-Ḥijjah 1036 AH (26 Aug. 1627 CE)</origDate> by <persName role="scr">‘Alī Jān ibn Ḥaydar ‘Alī</persName>
                  </origin>
                                 <provenance><p> Likely either restored for, or obtained by <persName type="standard" role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/19247044" key="person_19247044">Jonathan Duncan</persName>, who governed the <placeName type="province" ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7001518">Bombay Presidency</placeName> for sixteen years.</p></provenance>
                                 <provenance><p>After Duncan's death, his family sold his library through the <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7011781">London</placeName> firm of <persName role="auc" ref=" http://viaf.org/viaf/10201461" key="person_10201461">Samuel Leigh Sotheby (1805–1861)</persName> 
  where <persName role="fmo ins" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/32750828" key="person_32750828">Sir Graves Champney Haughton (1788–1849)</persName>, an early student at Fort William College who excelled in the study of several oriental languages, purchased this set as per his inscription on folio <locus from="1b" to="1b">1b</locus> dated <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1818-02">Feb. 1818</date>.
                                 </p></provenance>
                                 <provenance><p>Later owned by Persian scholar <persName type="standard"
                                    role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/20108923/" key="person_20108923"
                                    >Nathaniel Bland (1803–1865)</persName>, after whose death <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7011781" key="place_7011781">London</placeName>
                                    antiquarian dealer <persName type="standard" role="bsl"
                                       ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/5679225/" key="person_5679225">Bernard Quaritch
                                       (1819–1899)</persName> sold his oriental manuscripts to <persName
                                          type="standard" role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/97751058/"
                                          key="person_97751058">Alexander Lindsay, 25th Earl of Crawford
                                          (1812–1880)</persName> in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1866"
                                             >1866</date>.</p>
                                 </provenance>
                                 <provenance>
                                    <p>Purchased by <persName type="standard" role="dnr" key="person_f6379"
                                       >Enriqueta Rylands (1843–1908)</persName> in <date calendar="#Gregorian"
                                          when="1901">1901</date> from <persName type="standard" role="fmo"
                                             ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/9985420/" key="person_9985420">James Ludovic
                                             Lindsay, 26th Earl of Crawford (1847–1913)</persName>.</p>
                                 </provenance>
                                 <acquisition>
                                    <p>Bequeathed by <persName type="standard" role="dnr" key="person_f6379"
                                       >Enriqueta Rylands (1843–1908)</persName> in <date calendar="#Gregorian"
                                          when="1908">1908</date> to the <orgName type="corporation" role="rps"
                                             ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/312795145/">John Rylands
                                             Library</orgName>.</p>
                                 </acquisition>
                              </history>
